SW,<br><br>
I knew that you had taken my words seriously and I also knew there were possible ramifications. No need for you to apologize. <br><br>
Concerning religion. I used to go to church and was very active. Our preacher was a good fellow, yet every once in a while he would say something that I didn't quite agree with. Rather than talk behind his back, I would give him a call or drive over to his house and we would have a chat. Once we sort of made a spectacle of ourselves as we argued with each other at a church meeting. We agreed on many things, of course, but I firmly believe that we had a better relationship because we were able to work out our differences without getting nasty or personal. sort aired things out once in a while.<br><br>
When My dad died and when my only brother died several years back, our preacher was there for me and my family. He was a real comfort to my mom. All of our little bickerings were long forgotten. They had given way to friendship.<br><br>
In one of your posts, Bob, you stated that you were unable to forgive but would consider coexisting with those you were angry with. Sounds like a good plan to me.<br><br>
I also agree with you that Cook deserves respect. Some of the best friends I have would agree with what he says. We have to be careful that we have all types of friends - not just those with whom we agree or who agree with us.<br><br>
Thanks for your message Bob. It means alot to me. I'm sorry for any offense taken by you or Cook.
